{"title_page": "James Lukaszewski", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = James E. Lukaszewski\n| image       =Jim-Lukaszewski-Americas-Crisis-Guru-612x657-5.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1942|08|27}}\n| birth_place = Kewaunee, Wisconsin\n| death_date  =\n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| occupation  = Author<br>Crisis management consultant\n| known_for   = Founder and president of The Lukaszewski Group Division of Risdall Public Relations\n}}\n\n'''James E. Lukaszewski''' (loo-ka-CHEV-skee) is an author, speaker, crisis management consultant and president of The Lukaszewski Group Division, Risdall Marketing Group.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\">{{cite news|title=He'll manage crises but prefers to avert them // Planning can help companies avoid crises, said consultant James Lukaszewski, back in the Twin Cities after 25 years in New York.|author=TODD NELSON|publisher=STAR TRIBUNE (Mpls.-St. Paul)|date=27 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=bizjournals.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/twincities/news/2011/02/02/lukaszewski-joins-risdall-mckinney-pr.html|title=Lukaszewski joins Risdall McKinney PR|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/09/business/the-media-business-anonymous-sources-given-advice.html|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS; Anonymous Sources Given Advice|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"All Stars\">{{cite news|title=PR News All -Stars Issue|date=19 October 2005|publisher=PR News|volume=61|issue=40}}</ref><ref name=\"New York Times2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/14/nyregion/in-business-program-to-help-businesses-in-public-relations-efforts.html|title=IN BUSINESS; Program to Help Businesses In Public Relations Efforts|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Wall Street Journal\">{{cite news|title=Oklahoma City Bombing: The Aftermath Resuming Business After a Catastrophe|author=Kathleen Deveny|author2=Gautam Naik|date=21 April 1995|publisher=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite news|title=Bothered and Bewildered; Maryland's 'Blair Witch' Town Tries to Prepare for the Sequel|publisher=The Washington Post|date=October 27, 2000|author=David Snyder}}</ref> He is known as \u201cone of the PR profession\u2019s most sought-after strategists in the areas of crisis communication, litigation visibility management, reputation threats and other high-profile and high-stakes operations.\u201d<ref name=\"Lloyd Dennis\">{{cite news|title=James E. Lukaszewski, ABC, APR, Fellow PRSA: The Lloyd B. Dennis Distinguished Leadership Award.|publisher=Public Relations Tactics|volume=14|number=1|date=January 2007|pages=22}}</ref> He is a recipient of the Patrick Jackson Award for Distinguished Service to the [[Public Relations Society of America]] and PR News\u2019 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref name=\"All Stars\"/><ref name=\"Patrick Johnson\">{{cite news|title=James E. Lukaszewski honored for years of service to PRSA - Crisis communications expert receives 2004 Patrick Jackson Award.|publisher=Public Relations Tactics|volume=11|number=12|date=December 2004|pages=25}}</ref> Lukaszewski is a member of the [[Rowan University]] Public Relations Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"RowanU\">{{cite news|title=Make a Difference|author=LUKASZEWSKI, JAMES E.|date=July 2009|publisher=Vital Speeches of the Day|volume=75|issue=7|pages=331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nJames E. Lukaszewski was born on August 27, 1942 in Kewaunee, Wisconsin.<ref name=LLP>{{cite news|author=Barnes, D.|title=James E. Lukaszewski, The Master of Crisis Management.|publisher=Contemporary Legends of Public Relations}}</ref> In his youth, he was an active participant in the Viking Council, Boy Scouts of America, Explorer Scout-Minneapolis fire department\u2019s EX-1 rescue and first aid program.<ref name=LLP/> In 1960, Lukaszewski graduated from Robbinsdale High School in Minnesota, and enrolled at Macalester College. There, he studied the sciences and liberal arts before leaving the school in 1961, and returning in 1962. Later, Lukaszewski pursued a pharmacy degree at the [[University of Minnesota]], before eventually enrolling at the [[Metropolitan State University|Minnesota Metropolitan State College (MMSC)]] in St. Paul, MN. In 1974, he received his B.A. degree in political public relations from MMSC.<ref name=LLP/><ref name=IABC>{{cite web|url=http://mn.iabc.com/2013/04/24/member-spotlight-jim-lukaszewski/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131121172743/http://mn.iabc.com/2013/04/24/member-spotlight-jim-lukaszewski/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 21, 2013 |title=Member Spotlight: Jim Lukaszewski |accessdate=Nov 20, 2013 }}</ref> In 1975, MMSC was renamed Metropolitan State University.<ref name=Metro>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrostate.edu/msweb/community/alumni/alumni_awards.html|title=Alumni Awards|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 1973, Lukaszewski served as an adult intern in the Press Office of former Minnesota Governor [[Wendell Anderson|Wendell R. Anderson]].<ref name=IABC/> Following his internship, Lukaszewski became the Director of Publicity and Publications for the Minnesota Department of Economic Development.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/> He later became the agency\u2019s Deputy Commissioner.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/> In 1978 with his wife, Barbara, Lukaszewski founded the Minnesota-based Media Information Systems Corporation, a public relations firm that specialized in crisis management and media training.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=LLP/>\n\nIn 1986, Lukaszewski moved to New York City, where he became a partner at Chester Burger Company, the nation\u2019s first communications management firm.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=IABC/><ref name=\"Industry Week\">{{cite news|publisher=Industry Week|date=June 1, 1987|title=Bottom-up communications|author=JOHN H. SHERIDAN}}</ref> He also served as senior vice president and director of executive communication programs at Georgeson & Company.<ref name=\"New York Times\"/><ref name=Courant>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2009-07-12/news/1bizbrfs0712.art_1_crn-international-wins-award-media-information-systems-corporation-communications-distinguished-lecture-series|title=Biz Buzz|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> Lukaszewski founded The Lukaszewski Group Inc. in 1989.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=IABC/>\n\nLukaszewski became an adjunct associate professor of Communications at [[New York University|New York University's]] School of Continuing and Professional Studies in 1987.<ref name=IABC/> He worked in that capacity until 2009.<ref name=IABC/>\nIn 2004, [[Ball State University]] awarded Lukaszewski its National Public Relations Professional Achievement Award.<ref name=BSU>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsu.edu/adminapps/emailupdate/volume24/041604.htm |title=News for Ball State Employees |accessdate=Nov 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194910/http://www.bsu.edu/adminapps/emailupdate/volume24/041604.htm |archivedate=2015-09-23 }}</ref> He also won the Lloyd B. Dennis Distinguished Leadership Award in 2006.<ref name=\"Lloyd Dennis\"/>\n\nIn 2010, Lukaszewski dissolved The Lukaszewski Group Inc. and returned to Minnesota to become the founding president of The Lukaszewski Group division of Risdall McKinney Public Relations.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=bldr>{{cite web|url=http://www.bulldogreporter.com/taxonomy/term/2176 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131121172826/http://www.bulldogreporter.com/taxonomy/term/2176 |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 21, 2013 |title=Lukaszewski Joins Risdall McKinney Public Relations |accessdate=Nov 20, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Lukaszewski was recognized by the Minnesota [[Public Relations Society of America]] with the Donald G. Padilla Distinguished Practitioner award.<ref>{{cite news | title = Minnesota PRSA Honors Jim Lukaszewski with Donald G. Padilla Distinguished Practitioner Award | url = http://www.news.nom.co/minnesota-prsa-honors-jim-lukaszewski-8903240-news/ | publisher = News | accessdate = 26 May 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140528005820/http://www.news.nom.co/minnesota-prsa-honors-jim-lukaszewski-8903240-news/ | archive-date = 28 May 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref> He was recognized as one of Robbinsdale High School's Distinguished Alumni Hall of Fame.<ref>{{ cite news | url = http://post.mnsun.com/2014/05/10-robbinsdale-high-school-alumni-honored/ | title = 10 Robbinsdale High School Alumni Honored | author = Bowen, Joe | publisher = Minnesota Sun Post | date = 5 May 2014 | accessdate =  26 May 2014 }}</ref> Trust Across America named Lukaszewski a Top 100 Thought Leader in Trustworthy Business.<ref>{{ cite news | url = http://www.bulldogreporter.com/dailydog/article/pr-people-on-the-move/james-lukaszewski-named-a-top-100-thought-leader-by-trust-acr | publisher = Bulldog Reporter | title = James Lukaszewski Named a Top 100 Thought Leader by Trust Across America\n | date = 6 February 2014 | accessdate = 26 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Memberships ==\nLukaszewski is a member of the [[International Association of Business Communicators]], the [[Public Relations Society of America]] and [[ASIS International]].<ref name=IABC/><ref name=PRSACoF>{{cite web|url=http://www.prsa.org/intelligence/businesscase/onthecasewith/cases/view/10314/106/on_the_case_with_james_e_lukaszewski_abc_apr_fello#.UlIoXCSsiSo|title=On the Case with James E. Lukaszewski, ABC, APR, Fellow PRSA|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=ASIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.risdall.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/James-E-Lukaszewski-ASIS-member-confirmation-letter.pdf|title=ASIS Member|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610215838/http://www.risdall.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/James-E-Lukaszewski-ASIS-member-confirmation-letter.pdf|archive-date=June 10, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He served on ASIS International\u2019s Crisis Management and Business Continuity Council (CMBCC) until 2014. Lukaszewski is a member of the PRSA\u2019s College of Fellows (Fellow PRSA) and the PRSA\u2019s Board of Ethics & Professional Standards (BEPS).<ref name=BulldogBEPS>{{cite web|url=http://www.bulldogreporter.com/dailydog/article/lukaszewski-named-trust-across-americas-top-100-thought-leaders-list-trustworthy-bu|title=Lukaszewski Named to Trust Across America's Top 100 Thought Leaders List in Trustworthy Business Behavior for 2013|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> He has been a member of BEPS since 1992. In 2015, BEPS named Lukaszewski member emeritus.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.prsa.org/Intelligence/TheStrategist/Articles/view/11030/1109/An_Education_in_Ethics_Jim_Lukaszewski_APR_Fellow#.VYC0KvlVikq| title=An Education in Ethics: Jim Lukaszewski, APR, Fellow PRSA, Named Member Emeritus of BEPS| last=Frause| first=Bob| date=April 14, 2015| publisher=PRSA| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, he was selected as an IABC Fellow and began serving on the IABC Global Communication Certification Council (GCCC).<ref>[http://www.mnprsa.com/jim-lukaszewski-earns-fellow-designation-iabc/ Jim Lukaszewski Earns Fellow Designation from the IABC] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829051036/http://www.mnprsa.com/jim-lukaszewski-earns-fellow-designation-iabc/ |date=2015-08-29 }}. Catherine Roman. August 28, 2015. Minnesota PRSA. Retrieved October 7, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Authorship==\n\nLukaszewski is a member of the Boards of Professionals of The Public Relations Review, a contributing editor to Public Relations Quarterly, a member of the Editorial Board of Case Studies in Strategic Communication at [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|UNC-Chapel Hill]], and a contributing columnist to PR News.<ref name=PRNewsCE>{{cite news|title=Want to Keep Your Seat At The Table? Change Your Vocabulary|date=19 January 2004|publisher=PR News|volume=60|issue=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Public Relations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.journals.elsevier.com/public-relations-review/editorial-board/|title=Public Relations Review Editorial Board|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=UNCCH>{{cite web|url=http://cssc.web.unc.edu/editorial-board/|title=Editorial Board|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> He has published 19 monographs on communication subjects since 1994, twelve manuals and books, including ''Why Should the Boss Listen to You, The Seven Disciplines of The Trusted Strategic Advisor'', and ''Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication: What Your CEO Needs to Know About Reputation Risk and Crisis Management'' and has written numerous articles.<ref name=hlmr>{{cite web|url=http://www.holmesreport.com/news-info/9849/Crisis-Expert-Lukaszewski-Joins-Risdall-McKinney.aspx|title=Crisis Expert Lukaszewski Joins Risdall McKinney|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication'' was one of Soundview's Best Business Books of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.summary.com/book-summaries/_/Lukaszewski-on-Crisis-Communication/|title=Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication|publisher=Soundview|accessdate=26 Feb 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Published authorship===\n\n:* The Minnesota Publicity Handbook (with Barbara B. Lukaszewski)<ref name=Book1>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Minnesota_Publicity_Handbook.html?id=fGxJGwAACAAJ|title=The Minnesota Publicity Handbook|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:* The Twin Cities Publicity Handbook (with Barbara B. Lukaszewski)<ref name=Copyright>{{cite web|url=http://www.copyrightencyclopedia.com/executive-action-checklists-january-through-september-1987/|title=Minnesota news media contacts & 5 other titles; books|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:* Executive Television Training Handbook<ref name=Book9>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Executive_Television_Training_Handbook.html?id=pFYzGwAACAAJ|title=Executive Television Training Handbook|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*The Publicity Handbook<ref name=Book2>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Publicity_Handbook.html?id=Ia6ftgAACAAJ|title=The Publicity Handbook|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Executive Action Emergency Media Relations Guide<ref name=Book3>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqoiPQAACAAJ&dq=Executive+Action+Emergency+Media+Relations+Guide&hl=en&sa=X&ei=c4fUUbr5B8ejyAGtx4CwCQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAQ|title=Executive Action Emergency Media Relations Guide|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Influencing Public Attitudes:  Strategies That Reduce the Media's Power<ref name=Book4>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LlWdPAAACAAJ&dq=Influencing+Public+Attitudes:+Strategies+That+Reduce+the+Media's+Power&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A4jUUbTYFcK6yAH1-IA4&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA|title=Influencing Public Attitudes|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Vol. I: War Stories and Crisis Communication Strategies, A Crisis Communication Management Anthology (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book5>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F6CwAAAACAAJ&dq=War+Stories+and+Crisis+Communication+Strategies,+A+Crisis+Communication+Management+Anthology&hl=en&sa=X&ei=KojUUaKsBKO9yQGXxoHwBQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA|title=War Stories and Crisis Communication Strategies|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Vol. II: Crisis Communication Planning Strategies, A Crisis Communication Management Workbook (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book6>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i7wKAgAACAAJ&dq=Vol.+II:+Crisis+Communication+Planning+Strategies,+A+Crisis+Communication+Management+Workbook,+%C2%A9+2000&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pUTgUc6YHuKQyQGhuoHwDA&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAQ|title=Crisis Communication Planning Strategies|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Vol. IV: Media Relations Strategies During Emergencies, A Crisis Communication Management Guide (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book6/>\n:*Vol. III: Crisis Communication Plan Components and Models (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book7>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5iTEAAAACAAJ&dq=Vol.+III:+Crisis+Communication+Plan+Components+and+Models,+%C2%A9+2005&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_0TgUcTqJofJyQGwv4GoCw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA|title=Crisis Communication Plan Components and Models|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Published authorship currently in print===\n\n:*''Why Should the Boss Listen to You? The Seven Disciplines of the Trusted Strategic Advisor'', Jossey-Bass\n:*''Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication: What Your CEO Needs to Know About Reputation Risk and Crisis Management'', Rothstein & Associates, Inc.<ref name=WorldCat>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/why-should-the-boss-listen-to-you-the-seven-disciplines-of-the-trusted-strategic-advisor/oclc/608622397&referer=brief_results|title=Why should the boss listen to you? : the seven disciplines of the trusted strategic advisor|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lukaszewski, James}}\n[[Category:People from Kewaunee, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = James E. Lukaszewski\n| image       =Jim-Lukaszewski-Americas-Crisis-Guru-612x657-5.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1942|08|27}}\n| birth_place = Kewaunee, Wisconsin\n| death_date  =\n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| occupation  = Author<br>Crisis management consultant\n| known_for   = Founder and president of The Lukaszewski Group Division of Risdall Public Relations\n}}\n\n'''James E. Lukaszewski''' (loo-ka-CHEV-skee) is an author, speaker, crisis management consultant and president of The Lukaszewski Group Division, Risdall Marketing Group.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\">{{cite news|title=He'll manage crises but prefers to avert them // Planning can help companies avoid crises, said consultant James Lukaszewski, back in the Twin Cities after 25 years in New York.|author=TODD NELSON|publisher=STAR TRIBUNE (Mpls.-St. Paul)|date=27 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=bizjournals.com>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/twincities/news/2011/02/02/lukaszewski-joins-risdall-mckinney-pr.html|title=Lukaszewski joins Risdall McKinney PR|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/09/business/the-media-business-anonymous-sources-given-advice.html|title=THE MEDIA BUSINESS; Anonymous Sources Given Advice|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"All Stars\">{{cite news|title=PR News All -Stars Issue|date=19 October 2005|publisher=PR News|volume=61|issue=40}}</ref><ref name=\"New York Times2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/10/14/nyregion/in-business-program-to-help-businesses-in-public-relations-efforts.html|title=IN BUSINESS; Program to Help Businesses In Public Relations Efforts|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Wall Street Journal\">{{cite news|title=Oklahoma City Bombing: The Aftermath Resuming Business After a Catastrophe|author=Kathleen Deveny|author2=Gautam Naik|date=21 April 1995|publisher=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite news|title=Bothered and Bewildered; Maryland's 'Blair Witch' Town Tries to Prepare for the Sequel|publisher=The Washington Post|date=October 27, 2000|author=David Snyder}}</ref> He is known as \u201cone of the PR profession\u2019s most sought-after strategists in the areas of crisis communication, litigation visibility management, reputation threats and other high-profile and high-stakes operations.\u201d<ref name=\"Lloyd Dennis\">{{cite news|title=James E. Lukaszewski, ABC, APR, Fellow PRSA: The Lloyd B. Dennis Distinguished Leadership Award.|publisher=Public Relations Tactics|volume=14|number=1|date=January 2007|pages=22}}</ref> He is a recipient of the Patrick Jackson Award for Distinguished Service to the [[Public Relations Society of America]] and PR News\u2019 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref name=\"All Stars\"/><ref name=\"Patrick Johnson\">{{cite news|title=James E. Lukaszewski honored for years of service to PRSA - Crisis communications expert receives 2004 Patrick Jackson Award.|publisher=Public Relations Tactics|volume=11|number=12|date=December 2004|pages=25}}</ref>Lukaszewski is a member of the [[Rowan University]] Public Relations Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"RowanU\">{{cite news|title=Make a Difference|author=LUKASZEWSKI, JAMES E.|date=July 2009|publisher=Vital Speeches of the Day|volume=75|issue=7|pages=331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n\nJames E. Lukaszewski was born on August 27, 1942 in Kewaunee, Wisconsin.<ref name=LLP>{{cite news|author=Barnes, D.|title=James E. Lukaszewski, The Master of Crisis Management.|publisher=Contemporary Legends of Public Relations}}</ref> In his youth, he was an active participant in the Viking Council, Boy Scouts of America, Explorer Scout-Minneapolis fire department\u2019s EX-1 rescue and first aid program.<ref name=LLP/> In 1960, Lukaszewski graduated from Robbinsdale High School in Minnesota, and enrolled at Macalester College. There, he studied the sciences and liberal arts before leaving the school in 1961, and returning in 1962. Later, Lukaszewski pursued a pharmacy degree at the [[University of Minnesota]], before eventually enrolling at the [[Metropolitan State University|Minnesota Metropolitan State College (MMSC)]] in St. Paul, MN. In 1974, he received his B.A. degree in political public relations from MMSC.<ref name=LLP/><ref name=IABC>{{cite web|url=http://mn.iabc.com/2013/04/24/member-spotlight-jim-lukaszewski/ |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131121172743/http://mn.iabc.com/2013/04/24/member-spotlight-jim-lukaszewski/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 21, 2013 |title=Member Spotlight: Jim Lukaszewski |accessdate=Nov 20, 2013 }}</ref> In 1975, MMSC was renamed Metropolitan State University.<ref name=Metro>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrostate.edu/msweb/community/alumni/alumni_awards.html|title=Alumni Awards|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nIn 1973, Lukaszewski served as an adult intern in the Press Office of former Minnesota Governor [[Wendell Anderson|Wendell R. Anderson]].<ref name=IABC/> Following his internship, Lukaszewski became the Director of Publicity and Publications for the Minnesota Department of Economic Development.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/> He later became the agency\u2019s Deputy Commissioner.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/> In 1978 with his wife, Barbara, Lukaszewski founded the Minnesota-based Media Information Systems Corporation, a public relations firm that specialized in crisis management and media training.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=LLP/>\n\nIn 1986, Lukaszewski moved to New York City, where he became a partner at Chester Burger Company, the nation\u2019s first communications management firm.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=IABC/><ref name=\"Industry Week\">{{cite news|publisher=Industry Week|date=June 1, 1987|title=Bottom-up communications|author=JOHN H. SHERIDAN}}</ref> He also served as senior vice president and director of executive communication programs at Georgeson & Company.<ref name=\"New York Times\"/><ref name=Courant>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2009-07-12/news/1bizbrfs0712.art_1_crn-international-wins-award-media-information-systems-corporation-communications-distinguished-lecture-series|title=Biz Buzz|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> Lukaszewski founded The Lukaszewski Group Inc. in 1989.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=IABC/>\n\nLukaszewski became an adjunct associate professor of Communications at [[New York University|New York University's]] School of Continuing and Professional Studies in 1987.<ref name=IABC/> He worked in that capacity until 2009.<ref name=IABC/>\nIn 2004, [[Ball State University]] awarded Lukaszewski its National Public Relations Professional Achievement Award.<ref name=BSU>{{cite web|url=http://www.bsu.edu/adminapps/emailupdate/volume24/041604.htm |title=News for Ball State Employees |accessdate=Nov 20, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923194910/http://www.bsu.edu/adminapps/emailupdate/volume24/041604.htm |archivedate=2015-09-23 }}</ref> He also won the Lloyd B. Dennis Distinguished Leadership Award in 2006.<ref name=\"Lloyd Dennis\"/>\n\nIn 2010, Lukaszewski dissolved The Lukaszewski Group Inc. and returned to Minnesota to become the founding president of The Lukaszewski Group division of Risdall McKinney Public Relations.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\"/><ref name=bldr>{{cite web|url=http://www.bulldogreporter.com/taxonomy/term/2176 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20131121172826/http://www.bulldogreporter.com/taxonomy/term/2176 |url-status=dead |archive-date=November 21, 2013 |title=Lukaszewski Joins Risdall McKinney Public Relations |accessdate=Nov 20, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Lukaszewski was recognized by the Minnesota [[Public Relations Society of America]] with the Donald G. Padilla Distinguished Practitioner award.<ref>{{cite news | title = Minnesota PRSA Honors Jim Lukaszewski with Donald G. Padilla Distinguished Practitioner Award | url = http://www.news.nom.co/minnesota-prsa-honors-jim-lukaszewski-8903240-news/ | publisher = News | accessdate = 26 May 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140528005820/http://www.news.nom.co/minnesota-prsa-honors-jim-lukaszewski-8903240-news/ | archive-date = 28 May 2014 | url-status = dead }}</ref> He was recognized as one of Robbinsdale High School's Distinguished Alumni Hall of Fame.<ref>{{ cite news | url = http://post.mnsun.com/2014/05/10-robbinsdale-high-school-alumni-honored/ | title = 10 Robbinsdale High School Alumni Honored | author = Bowen, Joe | publisher = Minnesota Sun Post | date = 5 May 2014 | accessdate =  26 May 2014 }}</ref> Trust Across America named Lukaszewski a Top 100 Thought Leader in Trustworthy Business.<ref>{{ cite news | url = http://www.bulldogreporter.com/dailydog/article/pr-people-on-the-move/james-lukaszewski-named-a-top-100-thought-leader-by-trust-acr | publisher = Bulldog Reporter | title = James Lukaszewski Named a Top 100 Thought Leader by Trust Across America\n | date = 6 February 2014 | accessdate = 26 May 2014 }}</ref>\n\n== Memberships ==\nLukaszewski is a member of the [[International Association of Business Communicators]], the [[Public Relations Society of America]] and [[ASIS International]].<ref name=IABC/><ref name=PRSACoF>{{cite web|url=http://www.prsa.org/intelligence/businesscase/onthecasewith/cases/view/10314/106/on_the_case_with_james_e_lukaszewski_abc_apr_fello#.UlIoXCSsiSo|title=On the Case with James E. Lukaszewski, ABC, APR, Fellow PRSA|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=ASIS>{{cite web|url=http://www.risdall.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/James-E-Lukaszewski-ASIS-member-confirmation-letter.pdf|title=ASIS Member|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610215838/http://www.risdall.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/11/James-E-Lukaszewski-ASIS-member-confirmation-letter.pdf|archive-date=June 10, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He served on ASIS International\u2019s Crisis Management and Business Continuity Council (CMBCC) until 2014. Lukaszewski is a member of the PRSA\u2019s College of Fellows (Fellow PRSA) and the PRSA\u2019s Board of Ethics & Professional Standards (BEPS).<ref name=BulldogBEPS>{{cite web|url=http://www.bulldogreporter.com/dailydog/article/lukaszewski-named-trust-across-americas-top-100-thought-leaders-list-trustworthy-bu|title=Lukaszewski Named to Trust Across America's Top 100 Thought Leaders List in Trustworthy Business Behavior for 2013|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> He has been a member of BEPS since 1992. In 2015, BEPS named Lukaszewski member emeritus.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.prsa.org/Intelligence/TheStrategist/Articles/view/11030/1109/An_Education_in_Ethics_Jim_Lukaszewski_APR_Fellow#.VYC0KvlVikq| title=An Education in Ethics: Jim Lukaszewski, APR, Fellow PRSA, Named Member Emeritus of BEPS| last=Frause| first=Bob| date=April 14, 2015| publisher=PRSA| access-date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, he was selected as an IABC Fellow and began serving on the IABC Global Communication Certification Council (GCCC).<ref>[http://www.mnprsa.com/jim-lukaszewski-earns-fellow-designation-iabc/ Jim Lukaszewski Earns Fellow Designation from the IABC] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150829051036/http://www.mnprsa.com/jim-lukaszewski-earns-fellow-designation-iabc/ |date=2015-08-29 }}. Catherine Roman. August 28, 2015. Minnesota PRSA. Retrieved October 7, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Authorship==\n\nLukaszewski is a member of the Boards of Professionals of The Public Relations Review, a contributing editor to Public Relations Quarterly, a member of the Editorial Board of Case Studies in Strategic Communication at [[University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill|UNC-Chapel Hill]], and a contributing columnist to PR News.<ref name=PRNewsCE>{{cite news|title=Want to Keep Your Seat At The Table? Change Your Vocabulary|date=19 January 2004|publisher=PR News|volume=60|issue=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Public Relations\">{{cite web|url=http://www.journals.elsevier.com/public-relations-review/editorial-board/|title=Public Relations Review Editorial Board|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref><ref name=UNCCH>{{cite web|url=http://cssc.web.unc.edu/editorial-board/|title=Editorial Board|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> He has published 19 monographs on communication subjects since 1994, twelve manuals and books, including ''Why Should the Boss Listen to You, The Seven Disciplines of The Trusted Strategic Advisor'', and ''Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication: What Your CEO Needs to Know About Reputation Risk and Crisis Management'' and has written numerous articles.<ref name=hlmr>{{cite web|url=http://www.holmesreport.com/news-info/9849/Crisis-Expert-Lukaszewski-Joins-Risdall-McKinney.aspx|title=Crisis Expert Lukaszewski Joins Risdall McKinney|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref> ''Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication'' was one of Soundview's Best Business Books of 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.summary.com/book-summaries/_/Lukaszewski-on-Crisis-Communication/|title=Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication|publisher=Soundview|accessdate=26 Feb 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Published authorship===\n\n:* The Minnesota Publicity Handbook (with Barbara B. Lukaszewski)<ref name=Book1>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Minnesota_Publicity_Handbook.html?id=fGxJGwAACAAJ|title=The Minnesota Publicity Handbook|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:* The Twin Cities Publicity Handbook (with Barbara B. Lukaszewski)<ref name=Copyright>{{cite web|url=http://www.copyrightencyclopedia.com/executive-action-checklists-january-through-september-1987/|title=Minnesota news media contacts & 5 other titles; books|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:* Executive Television Training Handbook<ref name=Book9>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Executive_Television_Training_Handbook.html?id=pFYzGwAACAAJ|title=Executive Television Training Handbook|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*The Publicity Handbook<ref name=Book2>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/The_Publicity_Handbook.html?id=Ia6ftgAACAAJ|title=The Publicity Handbook|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Executive Action Emergency Media Relations Guide<ref name=Book3>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqoiPQAACAAJ&dq=Executive+Action+Emergency+Media+Relations+Guide&hl=en&sa=X&ei=c4fUUbr5B8ejyAGtx4CwCQ&ved=0CDkQ6AEwAQ|title=Executive Action Emergency Media Relations Guide|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Influencing Public Attitudes:  Strategies That Reduce the Media's Power<ref name=Book4>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LlWdPAAACAAJ&dq=Influencing+Public+Attitudes:+Strategies+That+Reduce+the+Media's+Power&hl=en&sa=X&ei=A4jUUbTYFcK6yAH1-IA4&ved=0CC8Q6AEwAA|title=Influencing Public Attitudes|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Vol. I: War Stories and Crisis Communication Strategies, A Crisis Communication Management Anthology (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book5>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F6CwAAAACAAJ&dq=War+Stories+and+Crisis+Communication+Strategies,+A+Crisis+Communication+Management+Anthology&hl=en&sa=X&ei=KojUUaKsBKO9yQGXxoHwBQ&ved=0CDMQ6AEwAA|title=War Stories and Crisis Communication Strategies|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Vol. II: Crisis Communication Planning Strategies, A Crisis Communication Management Workbook (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book6>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=i7wKAgAACAAJ&dq=Vol.+II:+Crisis+Communication+Planning+Strategies,+A+Crisis+Communication+Management+Workbook,+%C2%A9+2000&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pUTgUc6YHuKQyQGhuoHwDA&ved=0CD0Q6AEwAQ|title=Crisis Communication Planning Strategies|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n:*Vol. IV: Media Relations Strategies During Emergencies, A Crisis Communication Management Guide (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book6/>\n:*Vol. III: Crisis Communication Plan Components and Models (with the Public Relations Society of America)<ref name=Book7>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5iTEAAAACAAJ&dq=Vol.+III:+Crisis+Communication+Plan+Components+and+Models,+%C2%A9+2005&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_0TgUcTqJofJyQGwv4GoCw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA|title=Crisis Communication Plan Components and Models|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Published authorship currently in print===\n\n:*''Why Should the Boss Listen to You? The Seven Disciplines of the Trusted Strategic Advisor'', Jossey-Bass\n:*''Lukaszewski on Crisis Communication: What Your CEO Needs to Know About Reputation Risk and Crisis Management'', Rothstein & Associates, Inc.<ref name=WorldCat>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/why-should-the-boss-listen-to-you-the-seven-disciplines-of-the-trusted-strategic-advisor/oclc/608622397&referer=brief_results|title=Why should the boss listen to you? : the seven disciplines of the trusted strategic advisor|accessdate=Nov 20, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lukaszewski, James}}\n[[Category:People from Kewaunee, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Lukaszewski"}
{"title_page": "Francis Fleming", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Francis Fleming\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = British English\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              = \n|imagesize          = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = 16th\n|office             = Attorney General of Ceylon\n|term_start         = 4 July 1883\n|term_end           = 1886\n|predecessor        = [[Bruce Burnside]]\n|successor          = [[Samuel Grenier]]\n|order2             = \n|office2            = \n|term_start2        = \n|term_end2          = \n|predecessor2       = \n|successor2         = \n|order3             = \n|office3            = \n|term_start3        = \n|term_end3          = \n|predecessor3       = \n|successor3         = \n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1842|7|31|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = London, Middlesex, England\n|death_date         = {{Death date and age|1922|12|4|1842|7|31|df=y}}\n|death_place        = London, Middlesex, England\n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = Francis Fleming\n|citizenship        = British\n|nationality        = English\n|party              = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = Constance Mary Kavanagh (1858\u20131950)\n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = Sec.-Lieut. Hugh Joseph Fleming (1895\u20131916)\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = British colonial administrator\n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Francis Fleming''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CMG|KCMG}} (31 July 1842 &ndash; 4 December 1922) ([[Chinese language|Chinese:]] \u83f2\u6797\u660e) was an administrator having appointments in no fewer than eleven British colonies.\n\nThe son of James Fleming (1812\u20131887), [[Queen's Counsel|Q.C.]] of Dorset Square and Julia Matilda (1811\u20131875) daughter of Major John Canning (1775\u20131824) and niece of Francis Canning (1769\u20131831) of Foxcote [[Warwick]].\n\nHe attended [[Downside School]] near [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], and studied law at the [[Middle Temple]], and was called to the bar in 1866.\n\nThree years later, from 28 April 1869, he became acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate in [[Mauritius]] earning \u00a3700 per annum, successively followed by  Crown Solicitor (from 15 April 1872), acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate in Savanne (2 November 1872), acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate, and Poor Law Guardian in Flacq (1 March 1873), District and Stipendiary Magistrate in Black River (1 January 1874), and acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate in Moka.{{cite book |title=The Mauritius Almanac and Colonial Register |date=1874 |page=183}}</ref> Whilst in Mauritius he also went to Seyebelles as acting District Judge for four months.<ref>{{cite book |title=Report of the Commissioners|year= 1876|page=17|last1=Eyre|first1=G. E.}}</ref>\n\nFrom then held a succession of posts as district judge in [[Jamaica]] (1876-1878); [[Attorney-General of Barbados|attorney-general]] of [[Barbados]] and acting Chief Justice (from 1878); and acting Chief Justice of St. Lucia.\n\nThis was followed in 1880 as private secretary to Sir G. C. Strahan, administering the Government of the Cape, and in 1881, removed to [[British Guiana]] as a Puisne Judge from 1882 to 1883.  In 1883 was transferred to [[Ceylon]] as a Queen's Advocate, later becoming Attorney-General and acting Chief Justice.<ref>{{cite book |title=Men at the Bar|page=157|last1=Fleming|first1=Francis}}</ref>\n\nIt was December 1886, as he was to be awarded the Order of St Michael and St George<ref>{{cite book |title=The Solicitors' Journal Vol.34|year=1890|page=49|}}</ref>, he returned to Mauritius to take up the roles as colonial secretary and administrator (acting governor) from 24 February 1887 to December 1888.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Mauritius Almanac and Commercial Handbook|year=1922|page=54|}}</ref><ref>http://www.britishempire.co.uk/maproom/mauritius/mauritiusadmin.htm</ref>\n\nFor over a year he was [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Colonial Secretary]] of [[Hong Kong]] between 1890 and 1892<ref>{{cite book |title=The History of the Laws and Courts of Hong-kong...|year=1898|page=137|last1=Norton-Kyshe|first1=J. W.}}</ref> (years later the [[Fleming Road]] in [[Wan Chai]], Hong Kong is named after him).\n\nDuring his Administration as Governor-in-Chief at [[Sierra Leone]], from 16 May 1892 to January 1894, he witnessed the first systematic strike of the 800 men underpaid-payed labouring classes of the Royal Engineers' Department in the history of that colony, as it took place in the month of November 1892.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Short History of Sierra Leone...|year=1900|page=137|last1=Crooks|first1=J. J.}}</ref>\n\nFleming was [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George|knighted]] on 1 January 1892 and that same year he married Constance Mary Kavanagh (1858\u20131950), daughter of Maurice Dennis Kavanagh (1821\u20131899) and Mary Constantia ''n\u00e9e'' Clifford (1825\u20131898) and granddaughter of [[Hugh Clifford, 7th Baron Clifford of Chudleigh]]. Their only son Hugh Joseph (born 26 Jan 1895 in Warwick) became a Sec.-Lieut. and was killed in action during WWI on 24 August 1916 at Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Catholic Who's Who Vol. 10|year=1917|page=508|last1=Burnand|first1=F. C.}}</ref>\n\nFleming then took the post as governor of the [[Leeward Islands]] from January 1894 where he remained till his retirement in 1901.\n\nFleming died at the age of 8O, at his residence, No.9 Sydney Place, South Kensington, on 4 December 1922<ref>{{cite book |title=Obituary: West Indies Chronicle Volume 37|year=1922|page=568|}}</ref>. His will was probated the following month and his widow survived him by nearly three decades.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp79437/sir-francis-fleming|title=Sir Francis Fleming|work=National Portrait Gallery|accessdate=2011-03-24}} (web image not currently available)\n\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Attorney General of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Attorney-General of Barbados}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{Succession box \n  | title = [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Colonial Secretary]] of [[Hong Kong]]\n  | years = 1890-1892\n  | before = [[Frederick Stewart (colonial administrator)|Frederick Stewart]]\n  | after = [[George Thomas Michael O'Brien]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=Sir [[William Frederick Haynes Smith]]\n| title=[[Governor of the Leeward Islands]] | years=1895\u20131901\n| after=Sir [[Henry Moore Jackson]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleming, Francis}}\n[[Category:Chief Secretaries of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Leeward Islands]]\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:British colonial governors and administrators in the Americas]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General of the Colony of Barbados]]\n[[Category:British Mauritius people]]\n[[Category:Colony of Jamaica judges]]\n[[Category:British Guiana judges]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of British Ceylon]]\n[[Category:People of British Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Governors of Sierra Leone]]\n[[Category:British colonial governors and administrators in Africa]]\n[[Category:British colonial governors and administrators in Asia]]\n\n\n{{HongKong-bio-stub}}\n{{UK-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = \n|name               = Francis Fleming\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = British English\n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              = \n|imagesize          = \n|smallimage         = <!--If this is specified, \"image\" should not be.-->\n|alt                = \n|caption            = \n|order              = 16th\n|office             = Attorney General of Ceylon\n|term_start         = 4 July 1883\n|term_end           = 1886\n|predecessor        = [[Bruce Burnside]]\n|successor          = [[Samuel Grenier]]\n|order2             = \n|office2            = \n|term_start2        = \n|term_end2          = \n|predecessor2       = \n|successor2         = \n|order3             = \n|office3            = \n|term_start3        = \n|term_end3          = \n|predecessor3       = \n|successor3         = \n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1842|7|31|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = London, Middlesex, England\n|death_date         = {{Death date and age|1922|12|4|1842|7|31|df=y}}\n|death_place        = London, Middlesex, England\n|restingplace       = \n|restingplacecoordinates = \n|birthname          = Francis Fleming\n|citizenship        = British\n|nationality        = English\n|party              = \n|otherparty         =  <!--For additional political affiliations-->\n|spouse             = Constance Mary Kavanagh (1858\u20131950)\n|partner            =  <!--For those with a domestic partner and not married-->\n|relations          = \n|children           = Sec.-Lieut. Hugh Joseph Fleming (1895\u20131916)\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = British colonial administrator\n|profession         = \n|cabinet            = \n|committees         = \n|portfolio          = \n|religion           = \n|signature          = \n|signature_alt      = \n|website            = \n}}\n\n'''Sir Francis Fleming''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|CMG|KCMG}} (31 July 1842 &ndash; 4 December 1922) ([[Chinese language|Chinese:]] \u83f2\u6797\u660e) was a administrator having appointments in no fewer than eleven British colonies.\n\nThe son of James Fleming (1812\u20131887), [[Queen's Counsel|Q.C.]] of Dorset Square and Julia Matilda (1811\u20131875) daughter of Major John Canning (1775\u20131824) and niece of Francis Canning (1769\u20131831) of Foxcote [[Warwick]].\n\nHe attended [[Downside School]] near [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], and studied law at the [[Middle Temple]], and was called to the bar in 1866.\n\nThree years later, from 28 April 1869, he became acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate in [[Mauritius]] earning \u00a3700 per annum, successively followed by  Crown Solicitor (from 15 April 1872), acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate in Savanne (2 November 1872), acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate, and Poor Law Guardian in Flacq (1 March 1873), District and Stipendiary Magistrate in Black River (1 January 1874), and acting District and Stipendiary Magistrate in Moka.{{cite book |title=The Mauritius Almanac and Colonial Register |date=1874 |page=183}}</ref> Whilst in Mauritius he also went to Seyebelles as acting District Judge for four months.<ref>{{cite book |title=Report of the Commissioners|year= 1876|page=17|last1=Eyre|first1=G. E.}}</ref>\n\nFrom then held a succession of posts as district judge in [[Jamaica]] (1876-1878); [[Attorney-General of Barbados|attorney-general]] of [[Barbados]] and acting Chief Justice (from 1878); and acting Chief Justice of St. Lucia.\n\nThis was followed in 1880 as private secretary to Sir G. C. Strahan, administering the Government of the Cape, and in 1881, removed to [[British Guiana]] as a Puisne Judge from 1882 to 1883.  In 1883 was transferred to [[Ceylon]] as a Queen's Advocate, later becoming Attorney-General and acting Chief Justice.<ref>{{cite book |title=Men at the Bar|page=157|last1=Fleming|first1=Francis}}</ref>\n\nIt was December 1886, as he was to be awarded the Order of St Michael and St George<ref>{{cite book |title=The Solicitors' Journal Vol.34|year=1890|page=49|}}</ref>, he returned to Mauritius to take up the roles as colonial secretary and administrator (acting governor) from 24 February 1887 to December 1888.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Mauritius Almanac and Commercial Handbook|year=1922|page=54|}}</ref><ref>http://www.britishempire.co.uk/maproom/mauritius/mauritiusadmin.htm</ref>\n\nFor over a year he was [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Colonial Secretary]] of [[Hong Kong]] between 1890 and 1892<ref>{{cite book |title=The History of the Laws and Courts of Hong-kong...|year=1898|page=137|last1=Norton-Kyshe|first1=J. W.}}</ref> (years later the [[Fleming Road]] in [[Wan Chai]], Hong Kong is named after him).\n\nDuring his Administration as Governor-in-Chief at [[Sierra Leone]], from 16 May 1892 to January 1894, he witnessed the first systematic strike of the 800 men underpaid-payed labouring classes of the Royal Engineers' Department in the history of that colony, as it took place in the month of November 1892.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Short History of Sierra Leone...|year=1900|page=137|last1=Crooks|first1=J. J.}}</ref>\n\nFleming was [[Knight Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George|knighted]] on 1 January 1892 and that same year he married Constance Mary Kavanagh (1858\u20131950), daughter of Maurice Dennis Kavanagh (1821\u20131899) and Mary Constantia ''n\u00e9e'' Clifford (1825\u20131898) and granddaughter of [[Hugh Clifford, 7th Baron Clifford of Chudleigh]]. Their only son Hugh Joseph (born 26 Jan 1895 in Warwick) became a Sec.-Lieut. and was killed in action during WWI on 24 August 1916 at Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Catholic Who's Who Vol. 10|year=1917|page=508|last1=Burnand|first1=F. C.}}</ref>\n\nFleming then took the post as governor of the [[Leeward Islands]] from January 1894 where he remained till his retirement in 1901.\n\nFleming died at the age of 8O, at his residence, No.9 Sydney Place, South Kensington, on 4 December 1922<ref>{{cite book |title=Obituary: West Indies Chronicle Volume 37|year=1922|page=568|}}</ref>. His will was probated the following month and his widow survived him by nearly three decades.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp79437/sir-francis-fleming|title=Sir Francis Fleming|work=National Portrait Gallery|accessdate=2011-03-24}} (web image not currently available)\n\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2011}}\n{{Attorney General of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Attorney-General of Barbados}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{Succession box \n  | title = [[Chief Secretary for Administration|Colonial Secretary]] of [[Hong Kong]]\n  | years = 1890-1892\n  | before = [[Frederick Stewart (colonial administrator)|Frederick Stewart]]\n  | after = [[George Thomas Michael O'Brien]]\n}}\n{{Succession box\n| before=Sir [[William Frederick Haynes Smith]]\n| title=[[Governor of the Leeward Islands]] | years=1895\u20131901\n| after=Sir [[Henry Moore Jackson]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fleming, Francis}}\n[[Category:Chief Secretaries of Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Governors of the Leeward Islands]]\n[[Category:1842 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:British colonial governors and administrators in the Americas]]\n[[Category:Attorneys-General of the Colony of Barbados]]\n[[Category:British Mauritius people]]\n[[Category:Colony of Jamaica judges]]\n[[Category:British Guiana judges]]\n[[Category:Attorneys General of British Ceylon]]\n[[Category:People of British Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Governors of Sierra Leone]]\n[[Category:British colonial governors and administrators in Africa]]\n[[Category:British colonial governors and administrators in Asia]]\n\n\n{{HongKong-bio-stub}}\n{{UK-gov-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", 