{"title_page": "James Lomax Bardsley", "text_new": "[[File:James Lomax Bardsley.jpg|thumb|James Lomax Bardsley]]\n'''Sir James Lomax Bardsley''', M.D. (7 July 1801 \u2013 10 July 1876) was an English physician.\n\n==Life==\nBardsley was born at [[Nottingham]] on 7 July 1801. His professional education was first under the direction of his uncle, Dr. [[Samuel Argent Bardsley]], and subsequently at Glasgow and Edinburgh universities; he received the diploma of M.D. in 1823 at Edinburgh, and while a student there was elected president of the [[Royal Medical Society]].<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bardsley, James Lomax|volume=3}}</ref>\n\nIn 1823 Bardsley settled in [[Manchester]], and was appointed one of the physicians of the [[Manchester Infirmary]], a post which he held until 1843. He was associated with [[Thomas Turner (surgeon)|Thomas Turner]] in the management of the [[Manchester Royal School of Medicine|Manchester Royal School of Medicine and Surgery]], and took an active part in the early proceedings of the [[British Medical Association]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn 1834 he became president of the [[Manchester Medical Society]], and in 1850 a similar position in the [[Manchester Medico-Ethical Association]] was given to him. He was knighted as a distinguished provincial physician in August 1853. He died at Manchester 10 July 1876.<ref name=\"DNB\"/> He is buried in the graveyard of the now demolished church of St. Saviour at the junction of Upper Brook Street and Plymouth Grove, Chorlton-on-Medlock, Manchester.<ref>ww.rootschat.com/forum/index.php?topic=601969.0</ref>\n\n==Works==\nBardsley published a volume of ''Hospital Facts and Observations'' in 1830, wrote the articles on [[diabetes]] and [[rabies|hydrophobia]] in the ''[[Cyclop\u00e6dia of Practical Medicine]]'' (1833), and made other contributions to medical science, including the retrospective address in medicine at the annual meeting of the British Medical Association in 1837.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Bardsley, James Lomax|volume=3}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardsley, James Lomax}}\n[[Category:1801 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:People from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:English medical writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:English knights]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:James Lomax Bardsley.jpg|thumb|James Lomax Bardsley]]\n'''Sir James Lomax Bardsley''', M.D. (7 July 1801 \u2013 10 July 1876) was an English physician.\n\n==Life==\nBardsley was born at [[Nottingham]] on 7 July 1801. His professional education was first under the direction of his uncle, Dr. [[Samuel Argent Bardsley]], and subsequently at Glasgow and Edinburgh universities; he received the diploma of M.D. in 1823 at Edinburgh, and while a student there was elected president of the [[Royal Medical Society]].<ref name=\"DNB\">{{cite DNB|wstitle=Bardsley, James Lomax|volume=3}}</ref>\n\nIn 1823 Bardsley settled in [[Manchester]], and was appointed one of the physicians of the [[Manchester Infirmary]], a post which he held until 1843. He was associated with [[Thomas Turner (surgeon)|Thomas Turner]] in the management of the [[Manchester Royal School of Medicine|Manchester Royal School of Medicine and Surgery]], and took an active part in the early proceedings of the [[British Medical Association]].<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\nIn 1834 he became president of the [[Manchester Medical Society]], and in 1850 a similar position in the [[Manchester Medico-Ethical Association]] was given to him. He was knighted as a distinguished provincial physician in August 1853. He died at Manchester 10 July 1876.<ref name=\"DNB\"/> He is buried in the graveyard of the now demolished church of St. Saviour at the junction of Upper Brook Street and Plymouth Grove, Chorlton-on-Medlock, Manchester.<ref>ww.rootschat.com/forum/index.php?topic=601969.0</ref>\n\n==Works==\nBardsley published a volume of ''Hospital Facts and Observations'' in 1830, wrote the articles on [[diabetes]] and [[rabies|hydrophobia]] in the ''[[Cyclop\u00e6dia of Practical Medicine]]'' (1833), and made other contributions to medical science, including the retrospective address in medicine at the annual meeting of the British Medical Association in 1837.<ref name=\"DNB\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n;Attribution\n{{DNB|wstitle=Bardsley, James Lomax|volume=3}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bardsley, James Lomax}}\n[[Category:1801 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English medical doctors]]\n[[Category:People from Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:English medical writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:English knights]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Lomax_Bardsley"}
{"title_page": "James Lees", "text_new": "{{for|the Scottish nationalist activist and pathologist|James Lees (politician)}}\n\n'''James Lees''' (born February 14, 1924) was a maritime expert, and curator of the ship collection and Senior Conservation Officer at the [[National Maritime Museum]], [[Greenwich]].\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in 1924, James Lees served both in the [[Royal Navy]] aboard [[destroyer]]s and on [[Oil tanker|tankers]] in the [[Merchant Navy]].<ref name=camberpete>{{cite web|url=http://www.camberpete.co.uk/sailing_pages_new/the_masting_and_rigging_of_english_ships_of_war_1625_1860.html |title=The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War 1625-1860 |publisher=Camberpete's Naval Book Site |accessdate=17 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911151721/http://www.camberpete.co.uk/sailing_pages_new/the_masting_and_rigging_of_english_ships_of_war_1625_1860.html |archivedate=11 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his active service, Lees (often referred to as \"Jim\")<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Savours |first1= Anne |year=1993 |title=Shackleton, ''James Caird'', and Discovery |journal=[[Polar Record]] |volume=29 |issue=171 |page=343 |doi=10.1017/S0032247400024165 |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=5423684 }}</ref> had a passion for ship modelling, leading him to construct and restore many models of historic vessels.  Many of these are displayed across the world, most notably at the collection of the National Maritime Museum, of which Lees was curator and Senior Conservation Officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmm.ac.uk/collections/explore/object.cfm?ID=SLR0359&picture=5 |title=Warship (1588); Galleon; Spanish (SLR0359) |publisher=[[National Maritime Museum]] |accessdate=17 June 2011 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  His expertise on model restoration was utilised on items in \"The Tradescant Collection\", held at the [[Ashmolean Museum]], [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ashmolean.museum/ash/amulets/tradescant/tradescant07-04.html |title=The Catalogue: Model Ship |work=The Tradescant Collection |publisher=Ashmolean Museum |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nLees\u2019 1979 publication ''The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War: 1625\u20131860'', drawn from 15 years of research, is widely regarded as an authority and the definitive study of its respective field.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.finemodelships.com/Linklist-english.htm |title=Literature and links, museums, historic ships and replicas |last1= Czytko |first1=Michael |publisher=Finemodelships.com |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref>  The author\u2019s intention was to \"assist restorers of marine paintings in the difficult task of replacing obliterated rigging, as well as providing a handbook of technical information for the maritime and war historian\".<ref name=camberpete/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |title=The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War, 1625\u20131860 |year= 1979 |publisher=[[Conway Maritime Press]] |location=London |isbn=0-85177-136-X |oclc=5288163}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War, 1625\u20131860 |year= 1984 |edition=revised |publisher=[[Conway Maritime Press]] |location=London |isbn=0-85177-290-0 |oclc=12407251 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T0YF0TUlE2wC}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lees, James}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British curators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Scottish nationalist activist and pathologist|James Lees (politician)}}\n\n'''James Lees''' (born February 14, 1924) was a maritime expert, and curator of the ship collection and Senior Conservation Officer at the [[National Maritime Museum]], [[Greenwich]].\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in 1924, James Lees served both in the [[Royal Navy]] aboard [[destroyer]]s and on [[Oil tanker|tankers]] in the [[Merchant Navy]].<ref name=camberpete>{{cite web|url=http://www.camberpete.co.uk/sailing_pages_new/the_masting_and_rigging_of_english_ships_of_war_1625_1860.html |title=The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War 1625-1860 |publisher=Camberpete's Naval Book Site |accessdate=17 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911151721/http://www.camberpete.co.uk/sailing_pages_new/the_masting_and_rigging_of_english_ships_of_war_1625_1860.html |archivedate=11 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to his active service, Lees (often referred to as \"Jim\")<ref>{{cite journal |last1= Savours |first1= Anne |year=1993 |title=Shackleton, ''James Caird'', and Discovery |journal=[[Polar Record]] |volume=29 |issue=171 |page=343 |doi=10.1017/S0032247400024165 |url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=5423684 }}</ref> had a passion for ship modelling, leading him to construct and restore many models of historic vessels.  Many of these are displayed across the world, most notably at the collection of the National Maritime Museum, of which Lees was curator and Senior Conservation Officer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmm.ac.uk/collections/explore/object.cfm?ID=SLR0359&picture=5 |title=Warship (1588); Galleon; Spanish (SLR0359) |publisher=[[National Maritime Museum]] |accessdate=17 June 2011 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>  His expertise on model restoration was utilised on items in \"The Tradescant Collection\", held at the [[Ashmolean Museum]], [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ashmolean.museum/ash/amulets/tradescant/tradescant07-04.html |title=The Catalogue: Model Ship |work=The Tradescant Collection |publisher=Ashmolean Museum |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nLees\u2019 1979 publication ''The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War: 1625\u20131860'', drawn from 15 years of research, is widely regarded as an authority and the definitive study of its respective field.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.finemodelships.com/Linklist-english.htm |title=Literature and links, museums, historic ships and replicas |last1= Czytko |first1=Michael |publisher=Finemodelships.com |accessdate=17 June 2011}}</ref>  The author\u2019s intention was to \"assist restorers of marine paintings in the difficult task of replacing obliterated rigging, as well as providing a handbook of technical information for the maritime and war historian\".<ref name=camberpete/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{cite book |title=The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War, 1625\u20131860 |year= 1979 |publisher=[[Conway Maritime Press]] |location=London |isbn=0-85177-136-X |oclc=5288163}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Masting and Rigging of English Ships of War, 1625\u20131860 |year= 1984 |edition=revised |publisher=[[Conway Maritime Press]] |location=London |isbn=0-85177-290-0 |oclc=12407251 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T0YF0TUlE2wC}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lees, James}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British curators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Lees"}
{"title_page": "Dorrington, Shropshire", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Dorrington\n| country = England\n| region = West Midlands\n| static_image_name = Dorrington - geograph.org.uk - 36118.jpg\n| static_image_caption = Dorrington\n| population = 619\n| population_ref = in 2008\n| os_grid_reference = SJ476031\n| post_town = SHREWSBURY\n| postcode_area = SY\n| postcode_district = SY5\n| dial_code = 01743\n| constituency_westminster = [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n| civil_parish = [[Condover]]\n| unitary_england = [[Shropshire]]\n| lieutenancy_england = [[Shropshire]]|\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.623|-2.773|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Dorrington''' is a large village in [[Shropshire]], England, it is located {{convert|6|mi}} south of [[Shrewsbury]]. The population of the village was estimated as being 619 in 2008.<ref>ONS MYE Population Estimates 2008</ref>\n\nThe [[Cound Brook]] flows to the east of the village, and to the southwest is Netley Hall and Netley Old Hall Farm. The [[A49 road]] runs through the village, which has a number of businesses located both in a small business park and along the main road. There is a [[public house]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dorringtonshorseshoes.co.uk/|title=Dorrington's Horseshoes|website=d-horseshoes}}</ref> a [[Persian cuisine|Persian]] restaurant, a [[convenience store]], a [[butchers|butcher's shop]], a [[post office]] and numerous other small businesses. There is also a [[primary school]], a village hall and a [[Church of England]] church, dedicated to [[Edward the Confessor|Saint Edward]].\n\nTo the east is [[Great Ryton|Ryton]]. Both Ryton and Dorrington lie in the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of [[Condover]]. Dorrington forms a ward of the parish and sends four councillors to the parish council.\n\n==Railways==\nThe village did once have a railway station on the [[Shrewsbury and Hereford Railway]]. The station is now closed, although the modern [[Welsh Marches Line]] still runs through the village. On the site of the station's goods yard, which is located just to the east of the village, is now an [[oil depot]] and a [[Heavy equipment (construction)|plant]] hire depot.\n\n==Other public transport==\n[[Minsterley Motors]] route 435 (Shrewsbury-[[Ludlow]] and ''vice versa'') runs through Dorrington, on its way between Condover (to the northeast) and [[Church Stretton|the Strettons]] (to the south). The service runs Monday-Saturday.<ref>[http://www.minsterleymotors.co.uk/435%20Time%20Table.html Minsterley Motors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126030938/http://www.minsterleymotors.co.uk/435%20Time%20Table.html |date=2012-01-26 }} 435 Service</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nFuture statistician [[William Farr]] was effectively adopted by a local squire, Joseph Pryce, when Farr and his family moved to Dorrington from [[Kenley, Shropshire|Kenley]]. Pryce died in November 1828, and left Farr \u00a3500, which allowed him to study medicine in [[France]] and [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=694|title=Arnott, Neil|first=Bill|last=Luckin}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Listed buildings in Condover]]\n* [[Dorrington Lane]], an unrelated hamlet, in the extreme north-east of the county, near [[Woore]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Dorrington, Shropshire}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n\n\n{{Shropshire-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| official_name = Dorrington\n| country = England\n| region = West Midlands\n| static_image_name = Dorrington - geograph.org.uk - 36118.jpg\n| static_image_caption = Dorrington\n| population = 619\n| population_ref = in 2008\n| os_grid_reference = SJ476031\n| post_town = SHREWSBURY\n| postcode_area = SY\n| postcode_district = SY5\n| dial_code = 01743\n| constituency_westminster = [[Shrewsbury and Atcham (UK Parliament constituency)|Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n| civil_parish = [[Condover]]\n| unitary_england = [[Shropshire]]\n| lieutenancy_england = [[Shropshire]]|\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.623|-2.773|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Dorrington''' is a large village in [[Shropshire]], England, it is located {{convert|6|mi}} south of [[Shrewsbury]]. The population of the village was estimated as being 619 in 2008.<ref>ONS MYE Population Estimates 2008</ref>\n\nThe [[Cound Brook]] flows to the east of the village, and to the southwest is Netley Hall and Netley Old Hall Farm. The [[A49 road]] runs through the village, which has a number of businesses located both in a small business park and along the main road. There is a [[public house]],<ref>http://www.dorringtonshorseshoes.co.uk</ref> a [[Persian cuisine|Persian]] restaurant, a [[convenience store]], a [[butchers|butcher's shop]], a [[post office]] and numerous other small businesses. There is also a [[primary school]], a village hall and a [[Church of England]] church, dedicated to [[Edward the Confessor|Saint Edward]].\n\nTo the east is [[Great Ryton|Ryton]]. Both Ryton and Dorrington lie in the [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] of [[Condover]]. Dorrington forms a ward of the parish and sends four councillors to the parish council.\n\n==Railways==\nThe village did once have a railway station on the [[Shrewsbury and Hereford Railway]]. The station is now closed, although the modern [[Welsh Marches Line]] still runs through the village. On the site of the station's goods yard, which is located just to the east of the village, is now an [[oil depot]] and a [[Heavy equipment (construction)|plant]] hire depot.\n\n==Other public transport==\n[[Minsterley Motors]] route 435 (Shrewsbury-[[Ludlow]] and ''vice versa'') runs through Dorrington, on its way between Condover (to the northeast) and [[Church Stretton|the Strettons]] (to the south). The service runs Monday-Saturday.<ref>[http://www.minsterleymotors.co.uk/435%20Time%20Table.html Minsterley Motors] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120126030938/http://www.minsterleymotors.co.uk/435%20Time%20Table.html |date=2012-01-26 }} 435 Service</ref>\n\n==Notable people==\nFuture statistician [[William Farr]] was effectively adopted by a local squire, Joseph Pryce, when Farr and his family moved to Dorrington from [[Kenley, Shropshire|Kenley]]. Pryce died in November 1828, and left Farr \u00a3500, which allowed him to study medicine in [[France]] and [[Switzerland]].<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=694|title=Arnott, Neil|first=Bill|last=Luckin}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Listed buildings in Condover]]\n* [[Dorrington Lane]], an unrelated hamlet, in the extreme north-east of the county, near [[Woore]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Dorrington, Shropshire}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Shropshire]]\n[[Category:Shrewsbury and Atcham]]\n\n\n{{Shropshire-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Martinevans123", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dorrington,_Shropshire"}
{"title_page": "The Ocean Blue", "text_new": "{{redirect|Ocean Blue|the ABC song|Ocean Blue (song)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{refimprove|date=July 2015}}\n{{original research|date=June 2011}}\n{{tone|date=June 2011}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = The Ocean Blue\n| image               = The Ocean Blue.jpg\n| caption             = \n| image_size          =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| origin              = [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| genre               = [[Indie pop]], [[dream pop]], [[jangle pop]]\n| years_active        = 1986\u2013present\n| label               = [[Sire Records|Sire]]/[[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             = {{url|theoceanblue.com}}\n| current_members     = David Schelzel <br>Oed Ronne <br/>Bobby Mittan<br>Peter Anderson\n| past_members        = Steve Lau <br>Rob Minnig <br>Scott Stouffer\n}}\n\n'''The Ocean Blue''' is an American [[indie pop]] band formed in [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]], United States, in 1986. Its core original members included David Schelzel on lead vocals/guitar, Steve Lau on keyboards/saxophone, Bobby Mittan on bass guitar and Rob Minnig on drums and vocals.\n\n==Early career==\nThe members of The Ocean Blue first met in junior high school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mediafiveent.com/archive/viewprofile.php?id=285|title=Media Five Archive for The Ocean Blue|publisher=Media Five Ltd|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref> They cut a series of demos while in high school, with Scott Stouffer sitting in on drums. They managed to get two of these earliest recordings, \"On Growing Up\" and \"Wounds of a Friend\", included on a local radio station compilation in late 1986. The compilation also included very early work from friends and mentors of The Ocean Blue, noted local artists, [[The Innocence Mission]]. Rob Minnig would join as permanent drummer in 1987, and the classic line-up of Schelzel/Lau/Minnig/Mittan would continue through 1994.\n\n==Sire Records years==\nThe Ocean Blue's members were just teenagers and still in high school when they signed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-ocean-blue-mn0000486395/biography|title=The Ocean Blue - Artist Biography |author=Jason Ankeny|publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> a three-album deal in [[1988 in music|1988]] with [[Sire Records]], at the behest of Sire founder [[Seymour Stein]]. The Ocean Blue's self-titled album was recorded in London with producers [[John Porter (musician)|John Porter]] and Mark Optiz.\n\nThe band's busy calendar included U.S. touring and an appearance on one of the first episodes of ''[[Club MTV]]'', with [[Downtown Julie Brown]]. The first single, \"Between Something and Nothing,\" peaked at #2 on the [[Billboard charts|Billboard]] Alternative Songs chart, while its follow-up, \"Drifting, Falling\" peaked at #10.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/the-ocean-blue|title=The Ocean Blue Chart History|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> Two promotional videos were made for the songs and both received rotation on ''[[PostModern MTV]]'', with the latter video featuring the band in various locations in and around their hometown of [[Hershey, Pennsylvania]]. The band later joined [[The Mighty Lemon Drops]] and [[John Wesley Harding (singer)|John Wesley Harding]] on an extensive U.S./Canadian tour. All of this promotion helped the band sell well over 150,000 units of the first record.\n\nAfter recording in several New England studios, the band released their second album, ''Cerulean'', in 1991.<ref name=\"UT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2013/03/04/ocean-blue/1962263/|work=USA Today|title=Fave '90s band The Ocean Blue resurfaces|author=Whitney Matheson|date=2013}}</ref> The singles \"Ballerina Out of Control\" and \"Mercury\" both charted on the Billboard Alternative Songs chart, at #3 and #27, respectively.<ref name=\"auto\"/> Drummer [[Rob Minnig]] began to hone his song production and mixing abilities, which would later be reflected on the next album and its single [[B-sides]], which the band chose to produce themselves.\n\nThe final Sire Records release came in 1993 with ''Beneath the Rhythm and Sound''<ref name=\"UT\" />, which sold over 100,000 copies. The single \"Sublime\" peaked at #3 on the Billboard Alternative Songs chart.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe band contributed songs to the [[Eric Stoltz]] film ''[[Naked in New York]]'', released on April 13, 1994. For the duration of their 1993-1994 tour in support of ''Beneath the Rhythm and Sound'', the band toured as a five-piece group, with newly-added second guitarist Oed Ronne. [[Westwood One Radio Networks]] recorded the group's June 20, 1994 concert in [[Ventura, California|Ventura]], [[California]] and released it as a promotional-only CD, the band's only official live album.\n\nDuring this time, keyboardist/sax player and original member Steve Lau was becoming more interested in the music business and moved to [[New York City]]. His final appearance on a commercial release by the band came with the ''Peace and Light'' EP, featuring the album track \"Peace of Mind\" as well as two live performances and a previously unreleased track. Lau exited the band in late 1994 and Oed Ronne was brought in full-time. Lau later became a record executive with a Sire Records subsidiary known as Kinetic, a label specializing in indie dance music.\n\n==Mercury Records and indie releases==\nIn 1996, [[Mercury Records]] signed the band and released their fourth album, ''See the Ocean Blue'', that fall, which reflected the arrival of new guitarist Oed Ronne and the band's renewed interest in the music of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kordarecords.com/the-ocean-blue/|title=the ocean blue |website=Kordarecords.com|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> While Schelzel remained the predominant songwriter of the band, Ronne composed two tracks and sang lead on his song \"Behind.\"\n\n''See'' was released to lukewarm results, with the record company cancelling plans to film a video for the second single, \"Slide.\" Despite a nationwide tour, the band fell victim to the global record company mergers and purges that engulfed late 1996 and early 1997.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn 1999, the band recorded and self-released their fifth album, ''Davy Jones Locker''. Two years later, the album was resequenced, remastered and re-released on [[March Records]], with March releasing both \"Denmark\" and \"Ayn\" as EPs, each featuring three new B-sides. Shortly thereafter, [[Rob Minnig]] decided to leave the group after fourteen years, and Peter Anderson, a friend of the band from [[Minneapolis]], [[Minnesota]], was brought in for live shows and, eventually, permanent recording work.\n\nIn 2004, the band released the diverse six-song EP ''Waterworks'' on What Are Records?. That year, the group performed select dates around the U.S., recruiting [[The Owls]]' saxophonist Brian Tighes. [[The Orange Peels]]' [[Allen Clapp]] contributed music and production duties to the EP and, to reciprocate, Oed Ronne and Peter Anderson later contributed to Allen Clapp and The Orange Peels' album ''Circling the Sun'' the following year. In October of that same year, David Schelzel entered the studio to record a solo version of [[Adolphe Adam]]'s 1847 [[Christmas]] classic \"[[O Holy Night]]\". This song was available only as a digital download via the band's website for the 2005 holiday season.\n\nIn late 2005, the Ocean Blue's entire five studio album catalogue, as well as the ''Waterworks'' EP and the band's first four videos, became available for purchase on [[iTunes]].\n\nOn June 1, 2006, the Ocean Blue's Schelzel/Mittan/Ronne/Anderson line-up played its first ever South American concert, with a show at Teatro Rajatabla El Llonja, [[Barranco District|Barranco-Lima]], [[Peru]].\n\nIn July 2010, the Ocean Blue's long-unreleased studio track \"City Traffic\" was uploaded to Dailymotion and YouTube with an accompanying homemade video.\n\n==Comeback==\nIn December 2010, the band's website announced that a new record was in the works. The website also offered a free Christmas download of a newly recorded cover version of the ancient Basque carol \"The Angel Gabriel from Heaven Came\", done by David Schelzel and Don Peris (of [[The Innocence Mission]]).\n\nIn December 2011, the band's website announced that another free Christmas download was available via the band's Facebook page. The release was a cover version of \"[[Walking in the Air]]\", a song written by Howard Blake and first showcased in the 1982 animated film ''[[The Snowman]]'', adapted from Raymond Briggs' noted 1978 children's novel of the same name. Similar to the previous year's holiday download, the recording was performed by David Schelzel and Don Peris.\n\nOn January 12, 2013, the band performed their first gig since 2006, performing at the Korda Records Showcase in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Korda Records was a new independent label formed by several artists, including The Ocean Blue's David Schelzel.\n\nOn March 6, 2013, the band released \"Sad Night, Where is the Morning?\", the first single from their forthcoming new album, to radio and in digital and physical formats. On March 19, The Ocean Blue's sixth album, entitled ''Ultramarine'', was released on Korda Records. The band embarked upon a tour of key markets in the United States that concluded with dates in Paraguay and Peru.\n\nOn September 9, 2014, the band reissued their 2004 ''Waterworks'' EP as a full-length album, expanded with the addition of three extra tracks. The band supported the release with a brief, limited concert tour of six dates throughout the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brooklynvegan.com/the-ocean-blue-3/|title=The Ocean Blue reissuing Waterworks EP with bonus tracks, touring this fall, playing CMJ (dates, new track stream)|website=Brooklynvegan.com|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, the band worked with Sire and Rhino Records to reissue their first three Sire albums on vinyl. The band marked the occasion by performing the first two albums in their entirety at limited concerts throughout the U.S. In 2016, the band did a full South American tour. \n\nIn June 2019, the band released their eighth full-length album, ''Kings and Queens / Knaves and Thieves'', on Korda Records.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/06/16/733158520/david-schelzel-on-the-ocean-blues-kings-and-queens-knaves-and-thieves|title=David Schelzel On The Ocean Blue's 'Kings And Queens/Knaves And Thieves'|website=Npr.org|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> They also released a video for the song \"Therein Lies the Problem with My Life\" around the same time.\n\n==Personnel==\nDavid Schelzel \u2013 lead vocals, guitar (1986\u2013present)<br>\nBobby Mittan \u2013 bass guitar (1986\u2013present)<br>\nOed Ronne \u2013 guitar, keyboards, vocals (1993\u2013present)<br>\nPeter Anderson \u2013 drums (2000\u2013present)<br>\nRob Minnig \u2013 drums, keyboards, vocals (1986\u20132001)<br>\nSteve Lau \u2013 keyboards, saxophone, vocals (1986\u20131994)<br>\nScott Stouffer \u2013 drums (1986)\n\n== Discography ==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album details\n! colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p13846|pure_url=yes}}|title= allmusic.com - All Music Charts & Awards|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2010-06-15}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Sales\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! width=\"30\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]\n! width=\"30\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US Heat]]\n|-\n| 1989\n| align=\"left\"| ''[[The Ocean Blue (album)|The Ocean Blue]]''\n* Label: [[Sire Records]]\n| 155\n| \u2014\n| 150,000\n|-\n| 1991\n| align=\"left\"| ''Cerulean''\n* Label: Sire Records\n